{"id":"1908.04965","submitter":"Gil Bor","authors":"Gil Bor, Mark Levi","title":"Hill's equation, tire tracks and rolling cones","comments":"22 pages; 14 figures; v3 has a new title and added Remark 3.1","journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.1088/1361-6544/ab5e3d","report-no":null,"categories":"math.DG math-ph math.MP","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Louis Poinsot has shown in 1854 that the motion of a rigid body, with one of\nits points fixed, can be described as the rolling without slipping of one cone,\nthe 'body cone', along another, the 'space cone', with their common vertex at\nthe fixed point. This description has been further refined by the second author\nin 1996, relating the geodesic curvatures of the spherical curves formed by\nintersecting the cones with the unit sphere in Euclidean $\\mathbb{R}^3$, thus\nenabling a reconstruction of the motion of the body from knowledge of the space\ncone together with the (time dependent) magnitude of the angular velocity\nvector. In this article we show that a similar description exists for a time\ndependent family of unimodular $ 2 \\times 2 $ matrices in terms of rolling\ncones in 3-dimensional Minkowski space $\\mathbb{R}^{2,1}$ and the associated\n'pseudo spherical' curves, in either the hyperbolic plane $H^2$ or its\nLorentzian analog $H^{1,1}$. In particular, this yields an apparently new\ngeometric interpretation of Schr\\\"odinger's (or Hill's) equation $ \\ddot x +\nq(t) x =0 $ in terms of rolling without slipping of curves in the hyperbolic\nplane.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 14 Aug 2019 05:44:24 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Mon, 9 Sep 2019 17:58:49 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Sun, 1 Dec 2019 19:57:40 GMT"}],"update_date":"2020-04-22"}
